{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658588"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20783"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20783"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97040"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13658"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20783"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79656"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12631"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32871"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97040"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA tissue sample from an immunocompromised patient reveals slender gram-positive organisms arranged in branching filaments with a beaded appearance. The organisms stain positively with modified acid-fast stains.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for this infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bordetella pertussis","Nocardia species","Listeria monocytogenes","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Neisseria meningitidis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe microscopic findings are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003ENocardia species\u003C/strong\u003E infection. Nocardia appear as slender gram-positive organisms that form branching filaments with a beaded appearance due to irregular staining. A key diagnostic feature is that they are partially acid-fast, meaning they stain with modified acid-fast stains like Fite-Faraco. Nocardia infections are more common in immunocompromised patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be distinguished as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-positive rod that does not form branching filaments and is not acid-fast. It typically causes meningitis or septicaemia in immunocompromised patients.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-negative diplococcus that does not form filaments and is not acid-fast. It typically causes meningitis and septicaemia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBordetella pertussis\u003C/strong\u003E is a small gram-negative coccobacillus that does not form branching filaments and is not acid-fast. It causes whooping cough and primarily affects the respiratory tract.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-negative rod that does not form branching filaments and is not acid-fast. While it can cause various infections in immunocompromised patients, it does not present with the characteristic microscopic appearance described.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nocardia species are slender gram-positive organisms that form branching filaments with a beaded appearance due to irregular staining.","Nocardia species are partially acid-fast, staining with modified acid-fast stains like Fite-Faraco, which distinguishes them from Actinomyces species.","Nocardia infections typically cause a suppurative response with central liquefaction and surrounding granulation and fibrosis, without true granuloma formation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 363-364."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79656"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20783"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79656"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:40:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:41:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13658"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97040"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12438"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Bacterial infections","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-18T18:20:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T18:20:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag